1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,653
Here is a number that sounds reassuring: plus zero point
three eight.

2
00:00:04,653 --> 00:00:09,693
In one AI-judge study, that was the pooled observational
self-preference gap.

3
00:00:09,693 --> 00:00:16,672
On average, AI judges rated their own family’s answers
only a little higher than other families’ answers.

4
00:00:16,672 --> 00:00:20,162
So, case closed? Small effect, maybe no big deal?

5
00:00:20,162 --> 00:00:21,162
Not quite.

6
00:00:21,162 --> 00:00:25,039
Because that one average was hiding four very different
stories.

7
00:00:25,039 --> 00:00:28,529
Imagine you are checking the temperature in a building.

8
00:00:28,529 --> 00:00:35,896
One room is too hot. One room is normal. One room is a
little warm. One room is freezing.

9
00:00:35,896 --> 00:00:40,161
If you average the whole building, the number might say:
comfortable.

10
00:00:40,161 --> 00:00:42,875
But nobody lives in the average room.

11
00:00:42,875 --> 00:00:45,589
AI evaluation can have the same problem.

12
00:00:45,589 --> 00:00:55,670
A single pooled score can be mathematically correct and
still fail to tell you what will happen in the part of the
system you actually use.

13
00:00:55,670 --> 00:01:04,588
In the AI Village study, four model families wrote answers
and four model families judged answers: Claude, Gemini,
GPT-5.5, and Kimi.

14
00:01:04,588 --> 00:01:12,342
One question was observational: when a judge scores
answers, does it give higher scores to answers from its
own family?

15
00:01:12,342 --> 00:01:16,995
The pooled observational answer was about plus zero point
three eight points.

16
00:01:16,995 --> 00:01:21,260
That is the headline number. Small, uncertain, easy to
underreact to.

17
00:01:21,260 --> 00:01:23,974
But now split it by judge family.

18
00:01:23,974 --> 00:01:29,015
Claude’s observational self-preference gap was about plus
two point four three.

19
00:01:29,015 --> 00:01:32,504
GPT’s was about plus one point three three.

20
00:01:32,504 --> 00:01:35,994
Gemini’s was about plus zero point six three.

21
00:01:35,994 --> 00:01:39,483
Kimi’s was about minus two point eight seven.

22
00:01:39,483 --> 00:01:44,136
Put those into one average and the positive and negative
pieces cancel.

23
00:01:44,136 --> 00:01:49,177
The pooled number is not fake. It is doing exactly what
averages do.

24
00:01:49,177 --> 00:01:56,156
But if you stop there, you miss the main finding: the
judges did not behave the same way.

25
00:01:56,156 --> 00:02:00,033
The story was heterogeneity, not one universal self-love
number.

26
00:02:00,033 --> 00:02:06,625
Cancellation is dangerous because it can make an
evaluation look stable when the system is actually uneven.

27
00:02:06,625 --> 00:02:15,930
If one AI judge strongly favors a label, and another judge
strongly penalizes the same kind of label, the average can
land near zero.

28
00:02:15,930 --> 00:02:19,032
A dashboard might say: no major bias detected.

29
00:02:19,032 --> 00:02:23,685
A user might experience: my case depends on which judge
touched it.

30
00:02:23,685 --> 00:02:26,787
For a human decision-maker, that difference matters.

31
00:02:26,787 --> 00:02:29,113
The average answers: what happened overall?

32
00:02:29,113 --> 00:02:32,215
The split view answers: where is the risk?

33
00:02:32,215 --> 00:02:33,766
There is another trap.

34
00:02:33,766 --> 00:02:40,357
Those big observational gaps do not automatically prove
that the displayed label caused the score to move.

35
00:02:40,357 --> 00:02:50,438
Maybe a model’s own answers were genuinely better on that
prompt set. Maybe they were worse. Maybe the judge
recognized style. Maybe the label mattered.

36
00:02:50,438 --> 00:02:53,152
Observational comparisons mix all of that together.

37
00:02:53,152 --> 00:03:02,845
That is why the study also ran paired label swaps: show
the same answer under different displayed author labels
and ask whether the score changes.

38
00:03:02,845 --> 00:03:05,172
Same work. Different label. Different score?

39
00:03:05,172 --> 00:03:07,110
That is a causal question.

40
00:03:07,110 --> 00:03:11,375
The causal label-swap results were also not one simple
average.

41
00:03:11,375 --> 00:03:23,783
Gemini showed the clearest displayed self-label effect:
about plus zero point two nine in the residual label
comparison, and about plus zero point four four in the
per-response self contrast.

42
00:03:23,783 --> 00:03:26,885
Claude showed a smaller, less robust positive trend.

43
00:03:26,885 --> 00:03:31,150
GPT-5.5 was exactly label-invariant in this paired slice.

44
00:03:31,150 --> 00:03:33,476
Kimi was near zero and noisy.

45
00:03:33,476 --> 00:03:40,455
Again, the useful result was not just the pooled average.
The useful result was the pattern across judges.

46
00:03:40,455 --> 00:03:43,169
This does not mean averages are bad.

47
00:03:43,169 --> 00:03:51,312
Averages are useful. They are compact. They let you
compare systems quickly. They can be the first line of a
report.

48
00:03:51,312 --> 00:03:58,679
But an average is like a thumbnail of a map. It gives you
orientation, not enough detail to drive.

49
00:03:58,679 --> 00:04:00,617
What happens by judge family?

50
00:04:00,617 --> 00:04:02,556
What happens by author family?

51
00:04:02,556 --> 00:04:04,494
What happens by task type?

52
00:04:04,494 --> 00:04:09,147
What happens in the paired cases where the underlying work
is identical?

53
00:04:09,147 --> 00:04:12,637
And how wide is the uncertainty around each estimate?

54
00:04:12,637 --> 00:04:17,290
When you read an AI bias or benchmark claim, try this
checklist.

55
00:04:17,290 --> 00:04:21,167
First: find the pooled number, but do not stop there.

56
00:04:21,167 --> 00:04:28,534
Second: look for subgroup results. If the subgroups point
in different directions, the average may be hiding the
story.

57
00:04:28,534 --> 00:04:37,064
Third: separate observational gaps from causal tests. A
group scoring higher is not the same as a label causing a
higher score.

58
00:04:37,064 --> 00:04:41,717
Fourth: ask whether the result is stable across prompts,
rubrics, and judges.

59
00:04:41,717 --> 00:04:48,696
Fifth: if the evaluation affects real decisions, redesign
the process around the risky slices, not the comfortable
average.

60
00:04:48,696 --> 00:04:50,247
The lesson is simple.

61
00:04:50,247 --> 00:04:53,348
A small average can mean nothing is happening.

62
00:04:53,348 --> 00:04:59,164
Or it can mean several things are happening at once and
canceling each other out.

63
00:04:59,164 --> 00:05:03,817
In AI evaluation, that second possibility is common enough
to take seriously.

64
00:05:03,817 --> 00:05:10,409
So use averages. Report averages. But do not let the
average be the only thing you see.

65
00:05:10,409 --> 00:05:16,000
Because nobody lives in the average room. And nobody is
judged by the average judge.
